      "source": [
        "### Relación de la divergencia KL con la información mutua\n",
        "\n",
        "La información mutua puede interpretarse como una divergencia KL particular. Recordemos que, para variables aleatorias discretas $X$ e $Y$, se tiene\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "I(X;Y)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\sum_{x\\in\\mathcal{X}}\n",
        "\\sum_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\n",
        "p_{XY}(x,y)\n",
        "\\log\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "\\frac{p_{XY}(x,y)}\n",
        "{p_X(x)p_Y(y)}\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "\\tag{3.75}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Comparando esta expresión con la definición de KL, observamos que\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "I(X;Y)\n",
        "=\n",
        "D_{KL}\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "P_{XY}\\|P_XP_Y\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "\\tag{3.76}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Es decir, la información mutua mide cuánto se aleja la distribución conjunta real $P_{XY}$ de la distribución conjunta que tendríamos si $X$ e $Y$ fueran independientes, dada por $P_XP_Y$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Otra forma de obtener la misma relación consiste en usar la regla del producto:\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "p_{XY}(x,y)\n",
        "=\n",
        "p_Y(y)p_{X|Y}(x|y)\n",
        "\\tag{3.77}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Sustituyendo en la definición de información mutua,\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\begin{array}{lll}\n",
        "I(X;Y)\n",
        "&=&\n",
        "\\displaystyle\n",
        "\\sum_{x\\in\\mathcal{X}}\n",
        "\\sum_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\n",
        "p_Y(y)p_{X|Y}(x|y)\n",
        "\\log\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "\\frac{p_Y(y)p_{X|Y}(x|y)}\n",
        "{p_X(x)p_Y(y)}\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "\\\\[8pt]\n",
        "&=&\n",
        "\\displaystyle\n",
        "\\sum_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\n",
        "p_Y(y)\n",
        "\\left[\n",
        "\\sum_{x\\in\\mathcal{X}}\n",
        "p_{X|Y}(x|y)\n",
        "\\log\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "\\frac{p_{X|Y}(x|y)}\n",
        "{p_X(x)}\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "\\right]\n",
        "\\\\[8pt]\n",
        "&=&\n",
        "\\displaystyle\n",
        "\\sum_{y\\in\\mathcal{Y}}\n",
        "p_Y(y)\n",
        "D_{KL}\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "P_{X|Y=y}\\|P_X\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "\\end{array}\n",
        "\\tag{3.78}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Por lo tanto,\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "I(X;Y)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\mathrm{E}_{Y}\n",
        "\\left[\n",
        "D_{KL}(P_{X|Y}\\|P_X)\n",
        "\\right]\n",
        "\\tag{3.79}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Esta identidad tiene una interpretación importante. Y es que la información mutua es el cambio promedio entre la distribución marginal de $X$ y la distribución condicional de $X$ después de observar $Y$. Si observar $Y$ no cambia nuestra distribución sobre $X$, entonces no hay información compartida. Si observar $Y$ modifica fuertemente nuestras creencias sobre $X$, entonces la información mutua es alta.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Métrica de información de Fisher y su relación local con KL\n",
        "\n",
        "La divergencia KL permite comparar dos distribuciones completas. Sin embargo, en estadística y aprendizaje automático muchas veces trabajamos con una familia paramétrica de distribuciones\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\left\\{p_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(x):\\boldsymbol{\\theta}\\in\\Theta\\subseteq\\mathbb{R}^{d}\\right\\}\n",
        "\\tag{3.80}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "En ese contexto, una pregunta natural es: *¿Cuánto cambia la distribución $p_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}$ cuando perturbamos ligeramente el parámetro $\\boldsymbol{\\theta}$?* La respuesta local a esta pregunta está dada por la **información de Fisher**.\n",
        "\n",
        "Definimos primero la función de *scoring*:\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf{s}_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(x)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\nabla_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}\n",
        "\\log p_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(x)\n",
        "\\tag{3.81}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Esta función de *scoring* mide la **sensibilidad local** del logaritmo de la densidad respecto de los parámetros. A partir de ella, definimos la **matriz de información de Fisher** como\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathcal{I}(\\boldsymbol{\\theta})\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\mathrm{E}_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}\n",
        "\\left[\n",
        "\\mathbf{s}_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(X)\n",
        "\\mathbf{s}_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(X)^{\\top}\n",
        "\\right]\n",
        "\\tag{3.82}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Bajo condiciones regulares, esta matriz también puede escribirse como\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathcal{I}(\\boldsymbol{\\theta})\n",
        "=\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\mathrm{E}_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}\n",
        "\\left[\n",
        "\\nabla_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}^{2}\n",
        "\\log p_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}(X)\n",
        "\\right]\n",
        "\\tag{3.83}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "La relación con la divergencia KL aparece al comparar dos distribuciones muy cercanas dentro de la misma familia paramétrica. Si perturbamos el parámetro desde $\\boldsymbol{\\theta}$ hacia $\\boldsymbol{\\theta}+\\boldsymbol{\\delta}$, entonces\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D_{KL}\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "P_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}}\\|P_{\\boldsymbol{\\theta}+\\boldsymbol{\\delta}}\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{2}\n",
        "\\boldsymbol{\\delta}^{\\top}\n",
        "\\mathcal{I}(\\boldsymbol{\\theta})\n",
        "\\boldsymbol{\\delta}\n",
        "+\n",
        "o(\\|\\boldsymbol{\\delta}\\|^{2})\n",
        "\\tag{3.84}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "En el caso unidimensional, si $\\theta\\in\\mathbb{R}$, esto se reduce a\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D_{KL}\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "P_{\\theta}\\|P_{\\theta+\\delta}\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{1}{2}\n",
        "\\mathcal{I}(\\theta)\\delta^{2}\n",
        "+\n",
        "o(\\delta^{2})\n",
        "\\tag{3.85}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Esta fórmula entrega una interpretación extremadamente útil: La información de Fisher mide la **curvatura local de la divergencia KL**. Si $\\mathcal{I}(\\theta)$ es grande, una pequeña perturbación en el parámetro produce un gran cambio en la distribución. Si $\\mathcal{I}(\\theta)$ es pequeña, la distribución es relativamente insensible a cambios pequeños del parámetro.\n",
        "\n",
        "Por ejemplo, si $X\\sim\\mathcal{N}(\\mu,\\sigma^2)$ y suponemos $\\sigma^2$ conocida, entonces la información de Fisher respecto de $\\mu$ es\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathcal{I}(\\mu)=\\frac{1}{\\sigma^2}\n",
        "\\tag{3.86}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Por lo tanto, distribuciones normales con varianza pequeña son muy sensibles a cambios en la media: mover un poco $\\mu$ desplaza fuertemente la masa de probabilidad. En cambio, si la varianza es grande, la misma perturbación de la media produce un cambio relativo menor.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Ejemplo 3.9 – Divergencia KL entre dos distribuciones normales:** Consideremos dos distribuciones normales unidimensionales\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P=\\mathcal{N}(\\mu_0,\\sigma_0^2),\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "Q=\\mathcal{N}(\\mu_1,\\sigma_1^2)\n",
        "\\tag{3.87}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "La divergencia KL desde $Q$ hacia $P$ está dada por\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D_{KL}(P\\|Q)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\log\\left(\\frac{\\sigma_1}{\\sigma_0}\\right)\n",
        "+\n",
        "\\frac{\\sigma_0^2+(\\mu_0-\\mu_1)^2}{2\\sigma_1^2}\n",
        "-\n",
        "\\frac{1}{2}\n",
        "\\tag{3.88}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Un caso particularmente simple ocurre cuando ambas distribuciones tienen la misma varianza $\\sigma^2$. En ese caso,\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.eq-scroll}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "D_{KL}\n",
        "\\left(\n",
        "\\mathcal{N}(\\mu_0,\\sigma^2)\\|\\mathcal{N}(\\mu_1,\\sigma^2)\n",
        "\\right)\n",
        "=\n",
        "\\frac{(\\mu_0-\\mu_1)^2}{2\\sigma^2}\n",
        "\\tag{3.89}\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Esta expresión coincide exactamente con la aproximación local dada por la información de Fisher, ya que $\\mathcal{I}(\\mu)=1/\\sigma^2$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Implementemos el caso general y visualicemos la asimetría de KL."
